where "·" is the dot product and "×" is the cross product.
Conjugation, the norm, and reciprocal.
Conjugation of quaternions is analogous to conjugation of complex numbers and to transposition (also known as reversal) of elements of Clifford algebras. To define it, let formula_20 be a quaternion. The conjugate of "q" is the quaternion formula_21. It is denoted by "q"∗, , "qt", or formula_22. Conjugation is an involution, meaning that it is its own inverse, so conjugating an element twice returns the original element. The conjugate of a product of two quaternions is the product of the conjugates "in the reverse order". That is, if "p" and "q" are quaternions, then , not "p"∗"q"∗.
Unlike the situation in the complex plane,
